underground bunkers.

underground bunker networks.

gas station to poop in.

wondrous hotel if I was still alive!

It was silent, like a trained assassin. Or I was just
deafened by the truck's engine.

div.span:
The door lurched open. It was dark in the driver's seat,
shadowed from the moon. But I saw the barrel of a shotgun. I
heard a voice. It said...

div.span: And I got to see the stars in full force in the lonely night sky.

div.span: Yes, yes, I know it's an amazing story. Thank you very much.

div.span:
Yes, actually! Now I remember. The story went that his
truck's only fuel was fearful screams. Pretty scary, huh?

div.span:
The mountain was so steep I could lie down and watch the
stars and see my town all at once. What a memory.

div.span:
He knew I was scared sick of the stories about the mountain.
It was how he got me back for dissapointing him.

div.span:
It was beginning to rain. And a crazy wind was picking up,
turning this way and that, gathering up the pine needles off
the road and tossing them into my face.

div.span:
I was already pale and trembling from the bitter cold, but
now I was pale and trembling double!

div.span:
There was fog, and our old jalopy's headlights barely
worked. We got halfway down the mountain.

div.span:
I had been at a party thrown by a friend who lived alone up
on a mountain in his father's mansion, down the road behind
our school.

div.span:
When I was almost off the slope of the mountain, two lights
burst into view and raced towards me. I was blinded.

div.span: Yes! It growled, ''Stick em up.

div.span: But it was too cold to do that forever. So I got back on the road...

div.span: Oh, guess I did tell you I'd tell you! Well, here it goes.

div.span:
I got a ride home from my dad that night. He drove so fast I
always held onto my seat.

div.span:
Yes, actually! Now I remember. We called him the headless
trucker--such an original idea, I've never heard of it
anywhere else.

div.span: Hardly anyone came but me and my other friend. It was great!

div.span:
Anyway, I could barely see, and my breath hung in the air.
Did I mention it was winter?

div.span: No. Maybe I would have, but I was too quick. I leaped to the side of the road.

There was this rumor in our town of a possessed trucker that
circled around that mountain. He was said to be looking
for...

div.span:
At some point, nearly blind in the dark, I stumbled off the
road and caught a perfect view of our town through a
clearing in the trees. From up here, it was a glimmering
painting.

I was scared of the stories, but I'd gone up there many
times to see my friend. And he wasn't afraid of the mountain
--you couldn't be if you lived up there.
